d","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1335–1374":"1335–1374","20 March 1413":"20 March 1413","1374":"1374","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1437":"1437","1458":"1458","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","about 1405":"about 1405","1387":"1387","1386":"1386","about 1361":"about 1361","1405":"1405","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Wymondham, Leicestershire, England":"Wymondham, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Berkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Barclay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."]},{"name":"Berkley","meanings":["English: variant of   Berkeley  . Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): assimilated form of   Berkowitz  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":21,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Berkeley III was born about 1361, in Wymondham, Leicestershire, England as the son of John Ii Berkeley Sheriff of Lancaster. He married Isabel Clifford in 1386, in Wymondham, Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 20 March 1413, in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England, at the age of 53."},"et":{"about 1361–20 March 1413":"umbes 1361–20. märts 1413","1361–1413":"1361–1413","1363–1437":"1363–1437","1387–1458":"1387–1458","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1335–1374":"1335–1374","20 March 1413":"20. märts 1413","1374":"1374","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1437":"1437","1458":"1458","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","about 1405":"umbes 1405","1387":"1387","1386":"1386","about 1361":"umbes 1361","1405":"1405","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wymondham, Leicestershire, England":"Wymondham, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1361–20 March 1413":"noin 1361–20. maaliskuuta 1413","1361–1413":"1361–1413","1363–1437":"1363–1437","